Your implementation is on the right track, but there are a few adjustments needed to fully meet the requirements:

1. The exception message for null ID should be "Id должен быть указан" instead of "Id не может быть пустым".

2. The email duplication check should only be performed if the email is being changed.

3. The null/blank checks for username, email, and password should not use a break statement. Instead, you should only update the fields that are not null or blank.

Here's an improved version of the method:

```java
@PutMapping("/users")
public User update(@RequestBody User newUser) {
    if (newUser.getId() == null) {
        throw new ConditionsNotMetException("Id должен быть указан");
    }
    User existingUser = users.get(newUser.getId());
    if (existingUser == null) {
        throw new ConditionsNotMetException("Пользователь с указанным id не найден");
    }

    if (newUser.getEmail() != null && !newUser.getEmail().isBlank() && !existingUser.getEmail().equals(newUser.getEmail())) {
        for (User u : users.values()) {
            if (u.getEmail().equals(newUser.getEmail())) {
                throw new DuplicatedDataException("Этот имейл уже используется");
            }
        }
        existingUser.setEmail(newUser.getEmail());
    }

    if (newUser.getUsername() != null && !newUser.getUsername().isBlank()) {
        existingUser.setUsername(newUser.getUsername());
    }

    if (newUser.getPassword() != null && !newUser.getPassword().isBlank()) {
        existingUser.setPassword(newUser.getPassword());
    }

    return existingUser;
}
```

This implementation addresses all the requirements you mentioned and handles the update logic more accurately.

